Deep in the belly of the ancient Mayan jungle is an underwater kingdom unlike anywhere else. A vast aquifer system and millions of years of erosion have resulted in thousands of sinkholes, known as cenotes. Every cenote is completely unique - some are crystal clear, some are turbid. Some are virtually lifeless, some are important nurseries for countless species of fish. The term cenote comes from a word used by the lowland Yucatec Maya—tsʼonot—to refer to any location of freshwater. I have only experienced a handful of cenotes, but after this recent trip I am energized to spend a lot more time in them. Thank you @darksidedivers and @mirandajebowman for showing us around down there ⬇️🔦🕳️

Nurse sharks look pretty different from the stereotypical shark. They have silly little whiskers and no clearly visible teeth. The animals feed on a lot of shellfish and creatures hiding under corals, so their face and mouth has evolved for sucking small animals out of the sand or their hiding places. But if you look closely, they still have typical rows of shark teeth, so my expert advice is to not get bit by one. Footage is from Ambergris Cay, Belize and from Cozumel, Mexico. 👩‍⚕️🦈

Vacuums of the sea 🌱
Hey there, sea-loving friends! Have you ever seen a manatee in the wild? These gentle giants are truly a sight to behold. 🌊🐮 And if you’re lucky enough to spot them in the waters of Crystal River, Florida, you might just witness something truly amazing: manatees munching away on their favorite food, sea grass!

That’s right, folks. Manatees are like the vegetarians of the sea. They chow down on sea grass all day long, using their strong lips to graze the grass from the sandy bottom of the river. In fact, a full-grown manatee can eat up to 10% of its body weight in sea grass each day! 🌱👀

But why do manatees love sea grass so much? Well, for starters, it’s a great source of nutrition. Sea grass is packed with vitamins and minerals that help keep manatees healthy and strong. Plus, it’s easy to digest, which is important for an animal that spends most of its day lounging around in the water. 😴

But sea grass isn’t just tasty and nutritious for manatees - it’s also vital to their survival. Without sea grass, manatees would have a hard time finding enough food to eat, and their populations could decline. That’s why it’s so important to protect the habitats where manatees live and feed, so that these lovable “sea cows” can continue to thrive for generations to come. 🌊🐮

So there you have it, folks: manatees in Crystal River are like vegetarians at an all-you-can-eat salad bar! And with their round bodies and cute faces, it’s no wonder they’re the lovable “potatoes” of the sea. 🥔😂 If you ever get the chance to see these amazing animals in person, be sure to take a moment to appreciate their love for sea grass and the important role it plays in their lives. 🙌 #ManateeMunchies #SeaGrassForDays #VeggieLover #CrystalRiver #UnderwaterSaladBar #birdsunderwater #sdidivers #ocean #oceanlife #underwater #freediving #florida

Captured this stunning moment of a blue shark gracefully gliding through the mesmerizing light beams in the Pacific ocean. Did you know that blue sharks are one of the most fascinating species of sharks out there? Let me give you some quick facts!

First off, blue sharks are widely distributed across the world's oceans and can be found in both warm and cold waters. They're known for their slender bodies, blue-grey coloration, and long, pointed snouts. These sharks can grow up to 12 feet long and weigh over 400 pounds!

In terms of behavior, blue sharks are known to be highly migratory, traveling great distances in search of food and mates. They're also curious and may approach boats or divers out of curiosity, but are generally not considered dangerous to humans.

When it comes to conservation, it's important to note that blue sharks are one of the most heavily fished species of shark in the world. They're targeted for their meat and fins, which are used in traditional Asian medicine and shark fin soup. This unsustainable fishing is a major threat to blue shark populations worldwide.

But despite the threats they face, blue sharks have been around for a very long time. Fossil evidence shows that these sharks have been swimming in our oceans for at least 50 million years, and they've survived through some of the earth's biggest environmental changes. They're truly remarkable creatures!

So let's do our part to protect these beautiful animals and ensure that they continue to thrive in our oceans. Together, we can make a difference! 🌊🦈💙 #SaveTheSharks #BlueSharkLove #SanDiegoUnderwater #oceanlife #underwaterphotography #pacificocean #sharks

Spotted: one sleek and stunning moray eel on the move! 🪸
Every time I venture into the beautiful and mysterious underwater world, I find myself completely awestruck by the captivating creatures that inhabit it. Recently, I had the pleasure of photographing a Spotted Moray Eel as it gracefully swam along a vibrant coral reef in Palm Beach, Florida.
These eels are truly magnificent creatures, with their intricate pattern of dark spots over a lighter background. It’s fascinating to learn about their behavior and their role in the delicate ecosystem of the ocean. Spotted Moray Eels are a nocturnal species, often found hiding in crevices during the day and venturing out at night to hunt for prey. Their diet mainly consists of fish, but they also eat crustaceans and other small invertebrates.
One of the most intriguing things about these eels is their symbiotic relationship with cleaner shrimp. The eels open their mouths and allow the shrimp to enter to clean their teeth and remove parasites. It’s a fascinating example of mutualism in the ocean, where two species benefit from each other’s presence.
As an underwater photographer, I feel privileged to be able to capture these amazing moments and share them with the world. However, with the threats that the ocean faces, it’s more important than ever to raise awareness about the importance of ocean conservation. By taking small steps, we can make a big difference in protecting these incredible creatures and their habitats. Let’s do our part to preserve the beauty and wonder of the underwater world! 🐍🌊

Caught on camera: the elusive Green Eel Palpatine! 😱 
Can you see the resemblance? 🐍 

The green moray eel has an impressive set of primary jaws that are lined with rows of sharp teeth. These teeth are not designed for chewing but instead for grasping and tearing apart their prey. However, the eel’s unique pharyngeal jaws, located at the back of their throat, are specialized for grasping and manipulating prey. When hunting, green moray eels rely on their sense of smell to locate their prey, and once they have captured their prey, they use their pharyngeal jaws to move it to their primary jaws for consumption. The pharyngeal jaws are also useful for allowing the eel to swallow prey that might otherwise be too large to fit into its primary jaws.

Micro moments in a different world 🌞🍃🐠 
Light beams can appear to solidify underwater due to a phenomenon known as “total internal reflection.”
When light travels from a medium with a higher refractive index (e.g. air) to a medium with a lower refractive index (e.g. water), it bends or refracts. However, if the angle of incidence is greater than a certain critical angle, the light is reflected back into the higher refractive index medium instead of being refracted. This phenomenon is called total internal reflection.
Underwater, total internal reflection can occur when a light beam enters the water at a steep angle. The light is reflected back and forth between the surface of the water and the boundary between the water and air, creating a series of reflections that can make it appear as if the light beam is solid or tangible.
This effect is often seen in swimming pools, where sunlight shining through the water can create visible “beams” of light that seem to have a physical presence. However, the light beams themselves are not actually solid, and can be dispersed by disturbances in the water or other factors that disrupt the conditions necessary for total internal reflection.
As an underwater photographer, this phenomenon  is one my favorite muses to play with.

Walk along the riverbed.
You will come upon a nymph,
Aged and smooth
As a riverstone
Sighing and singing with 
The water’s flow
Ask her, “How are you, Nymph?”
And she will
Smile
Up at you and say
“I am but a tired soul
In a tired sea
Of tired souls.”
Her voice the soft bubbling of the river.

Walk among the trees.
You will come upon a dryad,
Ridged and furrowed
As the tree limb
Upon which she sat as she watched
The leaves fall with the autumn breeze
Ask her, “How long have you sat here, Dryad?”
And she will
Gaze
Down at you and say
“I grow and grow old
With the tree.
And the tree has grown tired.”
Her voice the raspy crinkle of the fallen leaves.

Walk amidst the flowers.
You will come upon a deva,
Light and sweet
As the honeysuckle she sat amongst
Watching and humming with
The many bees
Ask her, “Who are you, Deva?”
And she will
Frown
Away from you and say
“We, those of us that
Belong 
To this place,
We are Afraid. 
And we wish to no longer be Afraid.”
Her voice the wavering stems of delicate flowers.

The nymph chokes on her sisters' remains as
the dryad is cut down and shredded and the deva is
forced into restrained clay pots.

They cannot be freed by one
but by the response
of all.

-Response, by Cross Boundary

In fact, they have been observed seeking out divers for a "cleaning" from small fish that remove parasites and dead skin. Manta rays have a unique pattern of spots on their belly, which can be used to identify individuals and track their movements.⁠
⁠
These amazing animals have been observed exhibiting complex social behaviors, including group feeding and courtship displays. Manta rays also form long-term relationships with individual cleaning fish, returning to the same cleaning station for years.⁠
⁠
Unfortunately, manta rays are facing threats from overfishing and habitat destruction. ⁠

🐟 Unveiling Jawfish: Masters of seafloor design 🌊

Meet the jawfish, a fascinating and clever creature found in Florida’s coastal regions. These remarkable fish possess a unique ability to move shells and rocks outside their burrows, showcasing their resourcefulness and adaptation skills.

Jawfish, belonging to the Opistognathidae family, thrive in the warm waters of the Gulf of Mexico and the Atlantic Ocean. They have developed ingenious survival techniques, one of which involves manipulating their surroundings to ensure protection and secure food.

These agile fish create and maintain burrows in sandy or rubble-filled areas. When sensing danger or the need to fortify their dwelling, they use their powerful jaws to transport shells and small rocks, strategically arranging them around the entrance of their burrow. This creates a natural barrier, safeguarding them from predators.

Moreover, jawfish use their architectural prowess to attract prey. By selectively placing shells and rocks, they create a microhabitat that entices small crustaceans and other organisms. With lightning-fast reflexes, jawfish capture these unsuspecting prey items, utilizing their well-developed jaws for swift consumption.

The jawfish’s ability to move shells and rocks showcases their highly evolved sensory and motor capabilities. This behavior demonstrates their intelligence and adaptability within the marine environment.

These intricate behaviors have developed over millions of years, perfectly fitting the jawfish’s ecological niche. Witnessing their remarkable antics underwater is a captivating experience, reminding us of nature’s ingenious designs.

When exploring Florida’s mesmerizing underwater world, keep an eye out for these charismatic jawfish. Observing their remarkable ability to move shells and rocks is sure to leave you in awe of the wonders of the ocean. 🌊🐟

Finding good compositions for underwater photography can be challenging, but there are a few things you can do to help you get started:⁠
⁠
Scout the location: Before you start taking photos, take some time to explore the underwater environment and familiarize yourself with the layout. Look for interesting features like rock formations, coral reefs, or shipwrecks that could make good subjects.⁠
⁠
Pay attention to light: Light is crucial for photography, so be mindful of the direction and intensity of the light as you're exploring. Look for areas where the light is filtering through the water in interesting ways or creating dramatic shadows.⁠
⁠
Think about foreground, middle ground, and background: Just like with above-water photography, it's important to consider the composition of your image in terms of foreground, middle ground, and background. Look for elements that can help you create depth and visual interest in your photos.⁠
⁠
Use leading lines: Leading lines can help draw the viewer's eye through the image and create a sense of movement. Look for natural lines in the environment like rock formations or the curve of a coral reef.⁠
⁠
Experiment with angles: Don't be afraid to experiment with different angles and perspectives. Get low to the ground or shoot from above to create a unique point of view.⁠
⁠
Remember, the most important thing is to have fun and enjoy the experience of underwater photography. With practice and patience, you'll develop your own style and approach to capturing the beauty of the underwater world.⁠

Mother. Baby. Escort. 🐋🐳🐋 
Escorts are whales that stay with and watch out for mother-baby pairs. Often different escorts will compete for the role, with the bigger stronger males chasing off smaller ones. Females will also occasionally serve as escorts for the mom and baby. I don’t know a lot about these dynamics, but what I saw fascinated me and I can’t wait to learn more. 

#humpbackwhale #underwaterphotography #ocean

Humpback heat run 🔥🫧 
A large humpback whale charges ahead and blows a small steady stream of bubbles. The whale is blowing bubbles possibly in an attempt to disorient the other males chasing closely behind in this heat run. A heat run is where several male whales (sometimes dozens) chase a female, racing and battling amongst each other in an attempt to show dominance and ideally mate with the female. It’s a mating ritual that helps the female choose the most fit and powerful partner to impregnate her. 
We witnessed several heat runs and each one was dynamic and different from the last. The one thing they had in common is how fleeting they were. Whales are fast, and when they are racing each other they fly by like a pack of Greyhound busses on the highway. 🐋

Fascinating Fish Fact: Did you know that clownfish are champions of adaptability? They exhibit a unique phenomenon called sequential hermaphroditism. In their world, the largest clownfish in a group is the dominant female. If she disappears, the largest male transforms into a female to take her place. This incredible survival strategy ensures that clownfish can always continue their lineage in the vast and challenging ocean environment. 🐟💫

Hey there, fam! For those who might not know me well, let me give you a brief overview.⁠

I'm an underwater photographer originally from Denver, Colorado - yes, that's right, the land of the Rocky Mountains! I didn't start my photography journey in the local lakes. My passion for the ocean began as a child on the beaches of Melbourne, Australia. Later, I returned to Australia to work as a dive master on liveaboard boats traveling to the Great Barrier Reef, which sparked my interest in underwater photography.⁠
⁠
I completed degrees in Ecology and in Photojournalism at the University of Colorado Boulder. For some time, I worked as a cell biologist and robotics engineer, focusing on personalized medicine and oncology research. While I deeply enjoyed this work, my heart was more into scuba diving. I began making GoPro videos of seals in Elliot Bay, Seattle, which eventually led me to Monterey Bay, California - one of my favorite places. It's a spot where you're hit or miss with the weather and underwater conditions, but when it's good, it offers some of the most stunning underwater scenes on the planet.⁠
⁠
In California, I freelanced as an underwater videographer and worked on several documentary films. However, financial stability was a challenge, pushing me to find more lucrative ways to leverage my photography skills. That's when I jumped into marketing. I spent time growing my Instagram presence while learning the ropes of marketing, working at a scuba diving manufacturer.⁠
⁠
Four years later, with a wealth of marketing savvy, I launched my own company - Drumm Media LLC, in 2021. At Drumm Media, I blend my commercial photography and marketing skills, serving clients across various industries, including many clients that allow me to focus on underwater photography and content. I feel fortunate to work with incredible clients today and still get to use my underwater camera - and amazingly, get paid for it!⁠
